f thinking about potential Scala and Java cross-compilation. If a Java helper is in `src/test/java`, can a Scala test reference that class? Gradle with the Scala plugin might compile Java first, which is something I should keep in mind.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring Scala and Java Compilation**\\n\\nI'm considering how the Scala compile process can work with both Scala and Java files together. It looks like the Gradle Scala plugin can handle this, compiling sources from specific directories. I need to organize my source sets correctly, ensuring Java is compiled before Scala. There seems to be a possibility for Java files to be included, potentially even in Scala source directories. To be safe, Iâ€™m thinking it might be best to keep Java helpers under the Scala directory for clarity.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining Scala and Java Integration**\\n\\nThe user wants to place their Scala test files in src/test/scala, and I'm considering if a Java helper can be in the same directory. However, many infrastructures might expect specific file extensions, so it might be safer to use src/test/java without Scala references. I could call Java elements by their names without compile dependencies. But if the Scala tests reference the Java classes, those Java classes need to compile first. Itâ€™s important for native images that the classes are referenced correctly, or they may not be included.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Understanding Native Image Configuration**\\n\\nI'm exploring how the configuration for generating a native image works, specifically regarding loading classes. It seems all test classes are included in the native image, which is built with JUnit selecting those tests. Non-test helpers might also be included if they're reachable through metadata from the agent. The workflow starts by running the JVM with the agent before moving to native compilation. I need to remember to generate descriptor data strings 